-1 ROLLBACK BACKUP~
The {Rbackup{x command creates a backup copy of your character's pfile accessible by
immortals through the {Rrollback{x command.  This is a WORST CASE SCENARIO option to
be used by level 211 immortals only when absolutely necessary. We know that this mud
is unstable at times and use this to help pfiles who are affected by crashes.  Under
no circumstances will we rollback characters who have lost anything due to their own
actions.

If something has happened to your pfile that you think needs immortal attetnion, you
must bring it to our attention immediately via pray, note, or general jumping about.
If you delay in notifying the immortal staff, your chance of recovery is cut down by
quite a bit.   The most common occurrence of rollback use is when the mud crashes at
the exact moment of your death.  When the mud crashes, log the character you were on
right before the crash to be sure your pfile is intact.  If you fail to do this, you
will not be reimbursed.  If you get PK'ed and have sufficient time to recover all of
your belongings but fail to do so, you may plead your case to the immortals,  but it
is their right to decline your petition.

Please remember that rollback is a special feature on this mud.   We will only grant 
rollbacks when any losses are {Rsolely{x the fault of mud instability -AND- when the
player has contacted the immortals promptly.
~

-1 LOCKDOWN COPYOVER~
A copyover is very much like quitting the game and returning, except the login and logout are all automatic.
Lastly any items laying around you are not carrying will vanish And all the creatures in the game are reset.
Copyovers are done to make modifications to the code of the game ( How things work in the game ).

At 2 minutes before a copyover "Command LOCKDOWN" turns on.
This means you can not quest, read or write notes, reroll or arena.

At 60 seconds "Login LOCKDOWN" will turn on.
This means no one can login into the mud until the copyover is complete.
So, if you disconnect or quit during this time you will have to wait until the copyover has completed.

At any time if you wish to see how far long the countdown is type ctimer.

You are automatically saved just before the copyover happens.
Although, you may consider typing BACKUP.

~

